Memory Management

    WORKING WITH DYNAMIC MEMORY
    How to Picture Memory

        As a rule of thumb, every time you declare a pointer variable, 
        you should immediately initialize it with either a proper pointer or nullptr. 
        Don’t leave it uninitialized!

    Allocation and Deallocation
    Using new and delete

        As a rule of thumb, every line of code that allocates memory with new, 
        and that uses a raw pointer instead of storing the pointer in a smart pointer, 
        should correspond to another line of code that releases the same memory with delete.

        It is recommended to set a pointer back to nullptr after having freed its memory. 
        That way, you do not accidentally use a pointer to memory that has already been deallocated.